    "finalTextLength": 2389,
    "finalText": "Here’s the signal from Teams messages over the past week:\n\n- **Risk and uncertainty with early-stage projects:** Multiple messages across the week express unease about moving forward on projects like Eye Surgeons of Indiana while concept-level planning is still unsettled. The main concern is exposure to rework, lost time, or cost escalation if the owner/landlord delays or pulls back on approvals.\n- **Action paralysis due to incomplete owner decisions:** There are repeated threads flagging that workstreams (demolition, estimating) are on hold until the owner provides firmer direction on layouts and scope. Team members are worried about standing by without clear go/no-go authority, risking idle time or missed windows with subs.\n- **Schedule slippage on preconstruction tasks:** There’s tension around whether the pace of internal reviews, site walks, and estimate revisions are aligned with commitments made to owners/landlords. The worry is that slow cycles internally will be noticed externally and damage confidence.\n- **Procurement bottlenecks flagging early:** Some chatter indicates teams are already wary of procurement lead times — specifically for long-lead items — even at the schematic phase. There’s an anxiety that if the owner green-lights suddenly, the team isn’t positioned to move quickly into buyout.\n- **Owner communication gaps:** There is concern that owner-facing messaging is either lagging or unclear, especially regarding what decisions are needed from the owner, and the true impact of indecision on schedule and cost.\n\n**Summary:**  \nThe main worries are paralysis due to incomplete owner inputs, risk of wasted estimating/coordination, and not being ready to pivot fast if approvals land suddenly. The team is alert to owner delays, internal slowdowns, and early procurement exposures — and there’s underlying anxiety about not clearly surfacing these risks upstream.\n\n**What to do:**  \n1. Pin down owner decision points and escalate any missing or delayed inputs.\n2. Flag procurement exposure now — get a list of known long-lead items and prep contingency language for owners.\n3. Increase frequency of internal syncs on precon status and communication cadence to owners, so risks aren’t sliding by unreported.\n\nIf you want project-by-project specifics or attribution of concerns to individuals, say so — I’ll extract the direct messages and name names.",
